She now uses her production and organizational skills in her travel business to collaborate with her guests on unforgettable vacations.

.
Making new friends, especially as an adult, takes time, effort & energy just like everything else. Maybe you feel like planning social events is just one more thing to add to the to-do list. It might seem easier to choose loneliness and do life alone, but it only makes things harder in the long run. We are meant to be there for each other, and if you feel like no one is there for you - go out and be there for somebody else 👯‍♀️👩🏾‍🤝‍👩🏼

.
I constantly have to ignore what society says about single mothers. About how we’re an epidemic. How we’re ruining society. How we’re taking advantage of resources.
.
Every day, I have to choose to think differently than what others think of me. I have to choose to ignore the opinions and statistics. Because if I don’t, I will never be happy.
.
I have to choose joy. I have to choose peace. I have to choose confidence. I have to. For him, and for me. 🫶🏼

Happy #autismawarenessmonth! Trey wouldn’t be himself if he wasn’t autistic. I love our life together. I miss him when he’s at school and I cherish every moment spent with him. Somehow, I fall even more in love with him as he gets older. And as I learn about him, I learn more about myself. He is perfect as he is, but watching him grow is so much fun. I’m so grateful God blessed me with this sweet angel who makes me laugh all day long.
.
Please take some time to educate yourself on autism this month, and teach your kids too. Autistic people are people, special needs are human needs, and no one should ever feel left out/less than because they ride the short bus or go to a different classroom than their peers. Make this the month you stop using the word r*tarded and making jokes about being “slow”. Make this the month you invite the autistic classmate to your kid’s birthday party. Make this the month you treat neurodivergent people the same as everyone else… because we all deserve to belong. And then keep caring after this month.
.
We live in a straight white neurotypical world. But we can change it if we all make small efforts that combine over time. Thanks for reading 🫶🏼✨🌈🌸🦋

It was almost a decade ago, in 2013, that I became pregnant with my son and gained 65 pounds in less than 9 months.
.
Over the years I’ve tried to get back to my personal normal (which is different for everyone). But each time I lost any weight, eventually it would come back. Fast food and alcohol were my best friends whenever I went through a crisis in life, and my health would go out the window when I needed it most.
.
I’ve never had poor body image (don’t be jealous, I’ve had plenty of other issues lol). So every time I gained the weight back, I didn’t hate the way I looked- but I didn’t like the way I felt. I had a tough pregnancy with complications that resulted in major sciatica pain down my right side that gets worse when carrying excess weight.
.
Then I found out I had high cholesterol and knew something needed to change. When I started having sleep apnea for the first time in my life, and would wake up multiple times a night unable to breathe, that was the last straw.
.
It was a couple weeks later- a year ago now- when I started a program that I didn’t realize would change my life in multiple ways. It’s not a diet. It’s not a 21-day challenge, or 30 days or 75.
.
Health is a lifelong journey. Over the last year I’ve developed habits I will keep forever. And it feels so good, so fun & fulfilling, that I don’t want to stop this time 🥰
.
I have always been body positive, and always will be. It’s not about the way I look, it’s about the way I feel. Losing weight is a personal choice and should always be for the right reasons… because YOU want to. For yourself, and no one else. I will always support anyone doing what’s best for them. I’m just here if you want to hear about my way- no pressure, ever.
.
I’m so proud of myself for how far I’ve come in my transformation- mind, body, & soul. But this is just the beginning. And if you feel called to learn from me- you know how to reach me!
.
XOXO, Stephanie Stronger AKA Strength Queen 💪🏼👑
.

On this day 9 years ago, I was getting ready for the hospital to be induced at midnight due to painful hydronephrosis (a kidney issue) during my pregnancy. This is pretty common; it affects 68-100% of pregnant women after the 20th week of pregnancy. So why did it seem so bad for me?
.
After 11 hours of labor, Trey was born via C-section. He wouldn’t have survived otherwise. Because what we didn’t know at the time was that my hydronephrosis was caused from a bicornuate (misshapen) uterus. My type of uterus is shaped like a heart. Less than .5% of people assigned female at birth (AFAM) are born with this. Most people won’t be aware they have an irregularly shaped uterus until they’re pregnant and experience several miscarriages. 38% of these pregnancies do not make it to term. The ones that do are likely to have birth defects.
.
If you didn’t know some of these words, you’re not alone because neither did I. Women are not taught enough about their own bodies. I’m not sharing this to scare anyone but to raise awareness. My pregnancy was abnormal and should have been considered high-risk. More than likely, yours won’t be. But I’m glad I educated myself and this is your reminder to keep educating (& advocating) for yourself too 💘
.
Anyways… here is the most beautiful soul on earth who I would do it all over again for.

I started my online brand 13 years ago this month, in 2010 when the world and the internet were different. Social media was hardly a thing. We had MySpace and then Facebook and Twitter, but blogs were what podcasts are now. Everyone had one.
.
The difference was that the blogging world seemed smaller. Friendlier. For the most part, everyone supported each other. We'd happily comment, like, and share. We'd go to blogging conferences and meetups just for the fun of it.
.
We had webinars and clunky websites and Periscope before Instagram, TikTok, & going live. No competition, no monetization. There were no brand trips or ad campaigns. Just creativity and love. We were a family. The word "influencer" didn't exist.
.
Call me old or "cheugy" or whatever, but back in my day... the internet was our playground.
.
Now, social media feels more like a warzone. Battling with our opinions. Battling for attention. Our friends are flooded with ads and memes on their feeds and they can't see our stuff. But when something goes viral & everyone sees it, the comments are mostly negative and cruel. My word for the year is ✨HAPPINESS✨
.
This month I want to focus on detoxifying my life so we’re doing another no spend month, I’m doing dry January again, I’m still staying off of social media as much as possible. And at some point, I want to go through my closet again, try to sell or donate some things. Just really clear & cleanse my environment, my surroundings, my brain. Maybe unfollow some accounts that are no longer serving me.
.
Since my abusive relationship in 2020, I haven’t really done everything that I need to do to heal my nervous system. I did take some steps, like I went to therapy, I got back on medication, things like that. But I still was kind of bouncing from situationship to situationship, I definitely had a problem with alcohol and food for a while. And I feel like I’m still kind of overcoming some of those bad habits.
.
Obviously, we’re human, so it’s never going to be perfect but I do want to get to a place of my life where I feel very peaceful and at ease about where I am. 😌
.
And I haven’t felt that way in, definitely at least a year, if not more. I just want to get to a place in my life where I’m happy again. Honestly, that’s my main goal for the year. 💖 #hello2024

A different kind of before & after (TW: weight loss, body image)
.
I almost didn’t wear the dress. I refuse to wear shapewear because I’m uncomfortable in anything tight, and quite frankly I don’t care if people know I’m a regular middle-aged mom with a fupa.
.
Still, I almost didn’t wear it because even after losing 50lbs I still have love handles & hip dips. I wanted my outfit to look a certain way, for me.
.
No one tells you that in the process of losing weight you might start criticizing your body more because you’re paying more attention to it. I never really cared about my body but now it’s something I notice.
.
I was tempted to at least Facetune it for socials but as you can tell I’m really bad at it lol which is how you know my stuff is never photoshopped.
.
I guess what I’m saying is, if you’re on a health journey too and you’re actually feeling less confident than before, your feelings are valid. Sometimes it takes your brain some time to catch up and get used to what it sees in the mirror.
.
And it doesn’t matter what you look like anyways, what matters is that you’re taking care of yourself 💘 #weightlossjourney #weightlosstransformation #weightlossinspiration #weightlossgoals #weightlosstips
